FIRE B: THE BLEEDING STAIR
Location: The 7,000 Steps / High Hrothgar / the lower approach to the Throat of the World
Villain: The Dagon Cult - Gaelen the Root-Twister, ascended. This is his INTRODUCTION.
  The party never stopped him at the Eldergleam; he succeeded, planted the Seed of
  Desolation, and has now graduated from the corrupted forest to "the next garden" - the
  Throat of the World itself. "Faces of horn and fire." The true target is the Time-Wound:
  he means to widen Alduin's tear and let the Unmaking bleed through where the veil is
  thinnest. (See his character beats below - this is a villain the party has only felt at a
  distance until now. Their failure at the Eldergleam is wearing a face for the first time.)
Theme: Cosmic Horror / Sacred Desecration / Saijah's Crossroads
Conflict Type: Pilgrimage under corruption / Ritual disruption / Boss confrontation

The Courier: Klimmek, the provisioner who makes the weekly climb to the Greybeards. He
burst into the Bee and Barb addressing the whole room because what he saw needs a room. The
Waystones on the sacred path are bleeding black sap - the deep-forest rot, now on the most
holy ground in Skyrim. Grey-robed men with faces of horn and fire. And "the air felt wrong.
Like time was-" He ran without reaching the monastery. Saijah felt it: a violent localized
spike pointing southwest. The Throat of the World. The Dagon signature she has tracked since
Thornheart Grove. They are no longer contained to forests. They are between the world and
the sky, bleeding the stones.

Major Character Beats
- Saijah: Her arc converges here. The Dagon hunt she has carried since Thornheart Grove
  reaches its source-on-the-mountain. The migraine becomes a homing signal. Her Kynareth /
  Hircine crossroads (the white-stag offer she hesitated on at Krosulhah) is forced under
  pressure: the slow purifying path vs. the predator's quick kill. This is her fire.
- Bjorn: He carries two (now three) dragon souls and de-ages. The Greybeards summon and
  recognise the Voice. If the party reaches High Hrothgar, the question the campaign has
  been circling - "What if Bjorn is the Dragonborn?" - gets its first real test on the one
  ground designed to answer it. The Time-Wound is on this mountain.
- Davinia: The Crown of the Pale Lady resonates with corrupted time and frozen stasis. It
  will have opinions on a place where time itself feels wrong.
- Gaelen the Root-Twister (character intro): Do NOT play him as a ranting cultist. He is
  warm, direct, and absolutely sincere — the most genuine person in any room. His demeanor
  is not cold or detached; it is persuasive, caring, and deeply reasonable. He talks like
  an ally trying to get compatriots to listen, not a villain delivering a speech. His core
  conviction: the Aedra did not give mortals life, they gave them a CELL. They trapped the
  realm in linear time and fragile flesh and taught everyone to worship the very laws that
  keep them small and dying. To Gaelen, the unchanging Eldergleam was never sacred — it was
  a prisoner, like him. Every healing spell, every dragon slain, every act of "protecting
  the world" is just tightening the locks. He took a knife to his own true name to cut away
  the parts of his soul that required him to be weak and static (the same soul-carving as
  the Mehrunes' Razor ritual — see the Daedric Path doc; his dim Nymic armor and grafted
  Daedric arm are the evidence of that surgery). Dagon, to him, is not a destroyer — he is
  the one offering the key. The Unmaking is not annihilation; it is healing. He does not
  want to kill the party. He wants them to put down their weapons and stop suffering for a
  stagnant world.
  THE ALTERED SUBSTRATE: Gaelen's Nymic Surgery did not hollow him out or remove his
  emotions. It replaced his mortal emotional substrate with something categorically
  different. He has convictions, preferences, care — but these run on non-mortal
  architecture. His demeanor is warm and human; his experiential reality is not. The
  uncanny valley is subtle — Saijah senses it first, not as wrongness or evil, but as
  something alive and sincere that is not quite like her. He is not a villain. He is an
  ally on a different path, and the players should genuinely hesitate about whether he
  might be right.
  THE QUIET WISH: At some point during this module — ideally when he does not know the
  party is watching — the party overhears Gaelen facing the Time-Wound or the corrupted
  roots and saying quietly, to no one: "I want it to be perfect. Please... let it be
  perfect." This is not a plea, not desperation, not a crack in a mask. It is the sound
  of his altered architecture generating the closest thing it has to hope — a wish said
  to himself the way someone whispers "please let this work" over something they have
  invested everything in. He is not performing it. He does not know anyone heard it. The
  players will project grief or longing onto it. Every projection will be slightly wrong.
  That wrongness is the point. He should leave the table unsettled, not enraged — someone
  they cannot dismiss. If he escapes (likely — he is too good to spend in one module), he
  recurs across Act III/IV with a grievance now attached: the party finally showed up.

Section Structure
Section 1 (Ivarstead / The Foot of the Stair - Setup): The town at the base, frightened.
  Klimmek's supplies undelivered. The first bleeding Waystone. Saijah's signal locks on.
Section 2 (The Bleeding Steps - The Ascent): Climbing the 7,000 Steps as the corruption
  thickens. Each Waystone a station of escalating wrongness. Grey-robed cultists ambush from
  the rocks. The "time felt wrong" hazard - localized temporal distortion (actions out of
  order, doubled, or stolen). Environmental/cosmic-horror combat.
Section 3 (The Quarantine of the Masters - The Monastery): High Hrothgar, the Greybeards
  holding the summit against the corruption by Voice alone, exhausted. They will not come
  down the path - but the party reaching them opens the door to the Way of the Voice and
  the Time-Wound's significance. (They do NOT recognize Bjorn - the Greybeards have no
  special sight; no one can sense a Dragonborn. They DO know Word Wall locations.)
Section 4 (The Ritual at the Wound - Boss): The Dagon lieutenant's working at/near the
  Time-Wound - an attempt to widen the tear Alduin made, to let the Unmaking through where
  the veil is already thin. The boss fight under full temporal distortion.
Section 5 (The Sealing / The Cost): Disrupting the ritual. The path purified or merely
  staunched (a finger cut, not the body - echoing Darkwater). Saijah's crossroads ADVANCED,
  not resolved (resolution deferred to the first reckoning - Gaelen-kill / Razor). Whatever
  the Greybeards grant those who climbed to them.

The Reward: Access to the Greybeards / the Way of the Voice. The Bjorn-as-Dragonborn
  question advanced (never confirmed here). A Word of Power. Saijah's arc ADVANCED toward
  her choice, not settled. The sacred path reopened.
The Consequence (If Ignored): The Dagon Cult corrupts the Throat of the World and widens
  the Time-Wound. The Greybeards are cut off or fall; the Way of the Voice closes to the
  party. The Unmaking accelerates catastrophically. Dagon Cult Clock makes a major jump.
  Saijah's migraine becomes permanent and worsening - the source she failed to stop is now
  unreachable. This is the most cosmically dangerous fire to leave burning.

